    "narrative": "Our lineup for April 30th is headlined by **Yainer Diaz** (72.43) and **Taylor Ward** (71.19), who both benefit from favorable matchups against pitchers with xERAs near 5.00. **Yainer Diaz** is a top-tier play today, capitalizing on a 16% park factor boost against Young, while **Taylor Ward** similarly leverages an elite 19% SP skill advantage and a high-value #2 spot in the order. **Bryson Stott** (70.89) also demands attention; despite a slight penalty for opposing catcher arm strength, his dynamic platoon advantage against Houser makes him a cornerstone of today's production. While the order is less than ideal, **Jeremiah Jackson** (68.45) warrants inclusion due to the slow delivery of McCullers Jr., which significantly inflates our stolen base expectations\u2014a critical metric for LawDog given the scarcity of speed in our league.\n\nThe decision to bench **Jung Hoo Lee** (41.36) was the tightest call on the board. While he offers stability, he was ultimately pushed out by the higher efficiency ceilings of our corner and middle infielders, specifically **Geraldo Perdomo** and **Masyn Winn**, who provide more immediate category coverage. We must remain cautious with **Masyn Winn**, as he faces the formidable Skenes. Despite a wind-aided 5% boost, the SP skill penalty is substantial, effectively tethering his value to his speed rather than raw offensive output. Meanwhile, **Luis Arraez** (47.50) and **Matt Chapman** (48.59) are rostered primarily for their positional requirements against Mayza; we are accepting lower projected efficiencies here to avoid tapping into our bench depth, especially with **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** and **Cal Raleigh** enjoying a league-wide off-day. Keep a close eye on the weather and the finalization of the batting orders for **Lawrence Butler** and **Tyler Freeman**, as any late shifts could necessitate a pivot to ensure our SB-heavy strategy remains intact.",
